entry.title: [omnibox][ml][chrome://omnibox] Fix bugs & expand chart range
entry.content:
- The main change is to allow zooming out on the chart and seeing more

values. Previously, only -/+14 signals would be drawn. E.g. if the

original typedVisits was 20, then it'd be graphed from 6 to 34. Even

if you zoomed out, you'd see a tiny plot. With this CL, the range

extends to fill the canvas. Before/after:

https://screenshot.googleplex.com/6fye2qTuxaTta8x



- Caches ML requests. Since we're now regenerating plots as the user

pans/zooms, there's a lot of repeat requests.



- Skips charting the full model signals; only charts the small model

signals. The additional signals added latency with no benefit, since

they would be hidden anyways. The upside is improved performance. The

downside is an additional array of signals we have to keep consistent

when the model changes. Also removes debouncing when calculating the

charts; the improved performance made it unnecessary.



- Before, the chart had 3 coordinate systems we were converting between:

- the canvas where x=[0, 600px]

- the zoom/pan where initially x=[0, 1] but would change as the user

zooms/pans

- and the signal range where x=[-14, 14]. Before this CL, this was

constant. But with this CL, zooming/panning changed this too.

This CL merges the [0, 1], and [-14, 14] coordinates.



- Some other minor fixes to the chart.



- Fixes the 'Copied!' confirmation not appearing.



- Fixes a chart bug: when signals changed, the old graphs were supposed

to be cleared. But if the user moved their mouse over the graphs, the

old graphs would reappear.



- Fixes a crash: if the debug page was opened at startup, it would crash

because it would try to look up the value of an null optional returned

by the ML model service.

entry.title: Refactor Renderer ColorProvider instances to exist in blink::Page
entry.content:
This CL aims to change the way ColorProvider objects are stored and

accessed in Blink. Currently, ColorProvider instances exist in

Blink::WebThemeEngine which exists per renderer process. This can cause

unexpected behavior when multiple WebContents instances share a single

renderer.



This CL stores ColorProvider objects in blink::Page, which is

associated with each WebContents instance. This ensures that Blink uses

the correct ColorProvider for each WebContents, and does not rely on

the global NativeTheme web instance.



This is a step towards deprecating the use of NativeTheme as a color

source and moving towards having all color access routed through

ColorProvider instances (regardless if the color is a "native" or

"browser" color).



This refactor will also enable us support a block list for the

PageColors feature, which will allow users override forced colors

state via a browser setting.



This CL adds the ColorProviderColors mojo type map to allow

sharing of the type between Blink and content and avoid needless

marshaling back and forth between types.



ColorProviderColors are propagated to the renderer's Page class in

the following cases:

1. When the RenderView is first created.

2. When the ColorProvider associated with the WebContents changes.



Bug: 1430181

entry.title: [omnibox][chrome://omnibox] Fix bigint export and cap entries to 20
entry.content:
Some of the ML signals are bigints. `JSON.stringify()` doesn't support

bigint by default. This CL casts the bigints to strings when exporting

the JSON's via the 'Download' or 'Copy' buttons.



chrome://omnibox accumulates the autocomplete responses unbounded. This

can make the exports very large. 100 responses = 27mb. This can make it

hard to share; e.g. bugs.chromium.org limits attachments to 10mb. Asking

users to manually truncate the JSON is not good because a) most users

won't know how to b) some text editors will have a hard time opening

27mb files, and c) it's error prone. So this CL makes the export only

export the last 20 autocomplete responses. This is about 7mb, though the

exact size varies depending on the # of matches in the autocomplete

responses and will grow as we add more logged info per match. But it

seems safe for now.

Automated patch, intended to be effectively a no-op.



Context:

https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/cxx/c/nBD_1LaanTc/m/ghh-ZZhWAwAJ?utm_medium=email&utm_source=footer



As of https://crrev.com/1204351, absl::optional is now a type alias for

std::optional. We should migrate toward it.



Script:

```

function replace {

echo "Replacing $1 by $2"

git grep -l "$1" \

| cut -f1 -d: \

| sort \

| uniq \

| grep "^url/" \

| grep \

-e "\.h" \

-e "\.cc" \

-e "\.mm" \

-e "\.py" \

| xargs sed -i "s/$1/$2/g"

}



replace "absl::optional" "std::optional"

replace "absl::make_optional" "std::make_optional"

replace "absl::nullopt" "std::nullopt"

replace "absl::in_place" "std::in_place"

replace "absl::in_place_t" "std::in_place_t"

replace "\"third_party\/abseil-cpp\/absl\/types\/optional.h\"" ""
```

entry.title: [omnibox] Don't transfer sync old matches.
entry.content:
Autocompletion has a step where it transfers the matches from the

previous results to avoid async suggestions disappearing during sync

passes. This is pretty finicky, but necessary.



Currently, transferring skips:

a) matches from providers that already done.

b) actions which are recomputed for each pass.



It's safe to skip those because if they're still releveant to the new

input, they would have already been included in the new matches.



It's useful to skip those to avoid stale matches; e.g. 'github.com' when

the user's typed 'google.com'.



This CL adds' a 3rd case to skip:

c) match types that are always guaranteed to be sync; i.e.

search|url-what-you-typed matches.



These are safe to skip for the same reason; they'll be in the new

matches anyways.



These are useful to skip for the same reason, to avoid stale matches.

But that's relevant even more so in this case, since what-you-typed

suggestions are guaranteed to be stale when inputs change.

entry.title: aura: implement DesktopNativeWidgetAura reparenting
entry.content:
DNWA can have another DNWA as parent on initialization. However,

reparenting a DNWA using Widget::ReparentNativeView() causes many

issues, including but not exclusive to:

- the child content aura::Window will be freed twice on destruction.

- the child content aura::Window is parented to the content aura::Window

of parent DNWA. This results in the content window detached to its

owning accelerated window. The child content aura::Window should

instead remain to be the child of WindowTreeHost's aura::Window.



This CL plumbs reparenting into WindowTreeHost and fixes both issues.

On Windows, the HWND child / owned relationship is updated for

reparenting. Other platforms' accelerated widget will be updated in

follow-up CLs.

entry.content:
Use the new scripts_internal::SerializedUserScript and script

serialization methods when parsing content scripts in the extension

manifest. The flow now entails:

- Converting an api::content_scripts::ContentScript object to a

api::scripts_internal::SerializedUserScript object, then

custom logic to ensure we properly handle that when it's present on

the manifest content script entry.

entry.title: NavigationActivation prototype
entry.content:
NavigationActivation is a new object (exposed as

`navigation.activation`). It is updated when a new Document is

"activated": initial Document creation, restore from bfcache, or

(in a future CL) prerender activation. It has three pieces of state:

* `activation.entry`: The current NavigationHistoryEntry at the time

of activation.

* `activation.from`: The current NavigationHistoryEntry immediately

before activation (i.e., the entry we came from). This will be

null if the navigation was cross-origin, or if the previous entry

was not in the same-origin contiguous region of the back/forward

list that is available in `navigation.entries()`.

* `activation.navigationType`: The navigationType ('push', 'replace',

'reload', or 'traverse') of the navigation that activated the

current Document.



Note that `entry` or `from` may be a NavigationHistoryEntry that is

no longer present in `navigation.entries()` (e.g., when doing a

replace navigation, `activation.from` will be the replaced entry).

In that case, the entry will remain visible, but because it is

a "disposed" entry, its index will be -1 and attempting to

`navigation.traverseTo()` its key will be rejected.



Initial discussion: https://github.com/whatwg/html/issues/9760

Draft spec PR: https://github.com/whatwg/html/pull/9856
